description:
What if AI isnt just a tool - but the greatest threat to human connection weve ever faced?

Simon Sinek is a world-renowned entrepreneur, optimism expert, and founder of The Optimism Company, a platform which teaches human skills to leaders and organisations. He is also the bestselling author of books such as, Start With Why and Leaders Eat Last.

He explains:
鏝Why modern politics is killing your sense of purpose.
鏝Why weve forgotten how to be a good friend.
鏝How AI will create a generation of helpless humans.
鏝The number one secret skill AI cant learn.
鏝How human skills like empathy are vanishing.

comments.text:
We are living in the age of technology, an era where information is no longer locked away in books, institutions, or held by only a few. Today, wisdom is at our fingertips. With a single search, we can access the experiences, teachings, and insights of thousands of years in just moments.

With that kind of access and possibility available to us, it feels natural to ask:

Why are we still building societies based on old patterns of struggle, lack, and force?

What if, just what if, we allowed ourselves to evolve not through hardship, but through awareness, conscious choice, and shared wisdom?

What if we no longer needed to suffer in order to grow?

What if the pain endured by those who came before us didnt have to be repeated, but could become a bridge of insight, a foundation from which we build something different? Something softer. Something more aligned. Something more joyful.

As a generation who has walked through struggle, we carry with us the opportunity to transform that experience into wisdom, and to pass that wisdom forward not as a weight, but as a gift.

Instead of asking the next generation to walk through the same fire, we can offer them light.

Instead of passing down patterns of lack and struggle we can share tools of abundance.

Instead of shaping choices through fear, we can support them with clarity, the kind of clarity that comes from conscious awareness, from freely shared knowledge, and from truth spoken with care.

Children naturally learn through play, joy, curiosity, and creativity. So why do we, as adults, often believe that learning must only come through difficulty or struggle?

I do not believe that pain is the only teacher.

I do not believe that suffering is the only path to growth.

I believe, that joy and love can be powerful teachers.
That play can be a path of transformation.
That growth can come through conscious choice, presence, and compassion.

And I believe that by sharing what we have lived and learned, the experiences, the insights, and the truths we have come to know, we offer others the chance to grow with more ease, to move forward with more freedom, and to evolve through something lighter than what we knew.

This is how the shift begins.

This is how we begin to build a world where we are no longer just surviving, but truly living and thriving.
comments.author: @BawnAbundance

comments.text:
As a former AI developer, current AI marketing is a grift more than anything. It isn't all it's hyped up to be and I doubt that somehow magically we would be able to solve decades old problems in AI neural networks overnight (overlearning, singularity, hallucinations etc.). Problems that prevent AI ever being able to replace experience and workforce, let alone AGI. The developers themselves sometimes participate in the grift, but some of them also know their bosses are talking nonsense and the only reason they continue their work is because they need food on their table.

I stopped offering my expertise in AI and Data-analytics after I began seeing how it is being weaponized against people rather than to empower people. I think the way companies are now exploiting workers with AI is very unethical and I will not participate in this immoral behavior.

AI is not an innovation. Maybe an improvement, its always been present and we not only created it but we fed it. When we stopped caring about calculus and gave them a calculator, thats the start of the decline. Humanity changed when we discovered the power of fire. No more hunting (as much), preserving food, less chewing and etc. 

Humanity changed with the advent of machines, no more horses and manual labor in factories. The last change was the internet. It literally changed how we communicate. One to many suddenly took precedent over 1 to 1.  Thats the new norm? Right or wrong, its yet to be concluded

I personally dont think there is a turn around anymore. Weve gone too far. Maybe Im just the guy on the other side of the spectrum. But one thing is for sure: the threat of losing income and jobs has always been present and it has always been camuflagem by the interests of the powerful ones who have been controlling the engine for thousands of years. comments.text:
Okay I sent my last reply before I was done.  I really hate the statement that it's about the journey.  It's about the climb.  I think that is a bunch of bogus.  I have never made it to the top.  I never got the guy.  Not even a crush.  Never had someone I was crushing on hold my hand or kiss my lips.  Nothing.  And I am 58 years old.  I've written several books and publishers were willing to publish two of them.  But I never finished them so they where never published.  So I'm not successful.  I've made miniatures for miniature shops that I actually completed. And they sold instantly showing that people were interested in what I wanted.  I had people coming up to me in the shop asking me to make things for them.  Was it the climb?  Was it the journey?  Hell No!  It was how it felt good to sell my miniatures so quickly when the shop owner told me that I wasn't that good and that nobody would want my things.  When the shop owner told me that things sat on the shelf for up to a year before it sold.  But she'd let me try anyway.  And my stuff wouldn't stay on the shelves.  Was it the many tedious hours of sitting and trying to get each piece just right?  No.  That's what made me quit doing it.   It was the success that made me wish I didn't quit.  

Was it the journey or the climb in writing those books or trying to get a man?  Hell no.  Because I never made it to the top, it was a wasted effort and a loss that only led to heartache.  I never gained the prize.  The prize is what makes it.  Not the journey or the climb.  And the way I know that is because if you don't get the prize?  It is nothing but wasted time or pain.  I almost lost my life through suicide because I never got the man.  Not even for 1 minute.  Not even for one day.  It was never experiencing the prize that made me feel lick my life was wasted.  Like I was one of a quadrillion Stars that just faded out to Black and no one noticed or cared.  Because there was no prize.  Not ever.  The pain of longing to know what it feels like to have my fingers intertwined with someone I'm crushing on.  To know what it feels like to have him want me and feel like he loves me. . .  I will never experience that.  Never getting the prize.  I've accepted that now.  But I also know that it certainly isn't The climb.  That is just a concept that people just run with because it sounds good so it must be true.  . And most people follow the crowd when it comes to beliefs. Especially if it sounds good.  And no one really stops long enough to think if it's true.  

I spent hours writing my books.  Days months.  Where one of my children didn't feel like I was paying enough attention to her.  I was trying.  But I was also trying to make money for our family.  I spent all those months to just not be able to finish the book even though I had three publishing companies willing to publish it.  Real publishing companies.  They were willing to edit it, in the market it.  The whole nine yards.  Two of the publishers said they couldn't believe that I wasn't an author already.  But I am damaged goods.  Damaged from my past.  So I could not finish any of my books although every publisher I talked to was willing to publish them.  . What did I get out of that? Did I enjoy the climb or the journey?  My daughter won't let it go to this day even though she's 28 years old.  That I put so much work into my book that she felt like I was ignoring her.  It did damage.  And the climb and the journey wasn't worth it because the prize and the accomplishment never came.  It's the achievement.  The prize that makes it worthwhile.  Little Miss wrecking Ball would not have enjoyed the journey if she had not made it to the top.  I'm pretty sure there are a lot of people in Hollywood that are trying to make it big and they are failing.  And it's destroying them.  Eventually they will have to give up because they aren't making enough money and nobody wants them and all the dejection because they don't make it.  And they will feel like they wasted their life and like they weren't good enough.  Those that love them will feel like they were putting too much time into stuff that would come to no money.  And maybe they even left them.  Because there was no prize.  No achievement, the journey and the climb was nothing but pain.  That's just the truth of the matter.  And somehow I feel like I'm one of the only ones willing to admit it.
comments.author: @AnyaNiklaus
